<DOC><DOCNO> AP880712-0221 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 2218EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-Mummy-Children     07-12 0320</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Mummy-Children,0330</SECOND><HEAD>Woman Who Tended Husband's Corpse Regains Custody of Children</HEAD><DATELINE>GALESBURG, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A woman who was accused of child neglectafter authorities discovered she had been tending her husband'scorpse nearly nine years has regained custody of her children.   Knox County Judge Richard Porter restored Carole Stevens'parental rights following a review of several psychologicalexaminations conducted on the children, a 17-year-old girl and a14-year-old boy.   Porter said the children could return to their mother's home,where the mummified corpse of Carl L. Stevens was found Jan. 29 _nearly nine years after his death.   An autopsy revealed that Stevens, who was a diabetic, died May12, 1979, at age 39. His brown and shriveled corpse was discoveredin the family home where Mrs. Stevens, 42, had kept it bathed andclothed.   Mrs. Stevens, a registered nurse, had tended the corpse with thehelp of her two children and a house guest, Richard G. Kunce.   Authorities said the family's beliefs in a holistic health cultled them to believe they could communicate with Stevens through thebody and that he would return to life.   On Feb. 1, Mrs. Stevens and Kunce both pleaded guilty in KnoxCounty Court to a charge of failing to report the death. Kuncelater changed his plea to innocent. They also were charged withfelony forgery.   Mrs. Stevens was accused of fabricating a power of attorney forher dead husband in 1984 and using it to refinance a home mortgage.Kunce was charged with forgery for signing his name to the documentas a witness.   Mrs. Stevens pleaded guilty to the forgery charge and wasgranted probation. She was ordered to submit to psychiatrictreatment.   In a separate civil case, Mrs. Stevens admitted she was guiltyof child neglect for allowing her children to live with the corpse.The children were placed in foster care upon discovery of the body.</TEXT></DOC>